Network IDS (NSL-KDD dataset)

Jimmy Azar

Introduction

We build a network intrusion detection system based on the relative density one-class classifier (RDOCC) and the median one-class classifier (MOCC). We address both binary classification (normal-vs-attack), and multi-class classification with classes representing normal cases, probing attacks, DoS attacks, U2R attacks, and R2L attacks. The multi-class situation is handled by constructing 5 one-class classifiers followed by a majority voting scheme.

Add a binary label (attack/normal)

For each instance, add a binary label, Lb,specifying whether the object represents normal network traffic or an attack (anomaly). An anomaly can be any one of the attack labels that are different than “normal”. An anomaly is represented by the label “1” and a normal instance by the label “0”.

One-hot encoding of nominal features

To perform one-hot encoding of features, the training set and test set are first combined since the test set contains additional levels (categories) for some features. Such levels are not apparent in the training set. Once the combined data is encoded, the training set and test test are then re-split.

Relative density one-class classifier (RDOCC)

We implement a scalable version of the relative density one-class classifier to avoid memory overload when computing distance matrices. The implementation divides the work into manageable blocks.

rdocc_scalable <- function(xtrn, xq, k = 1, h = 1 , fracrej = 0.05, verbose = TRUE){
  #labeled training set xtrn should contain inliers only
  #labeled query points xq (test set)
  #method computes the following difference: ...
  #Parzen density using all training objects - average Parzen density of k nearest neighbors. 
  #k is a vector of number of neighbors to try out. 
  #h is the standard deviation of the Gaussian kernel. 
  #fracrej is the fraction of training objects to reject.
  
  if(!require("rdist")) install.packages("rdist")
  library("rdist")
  
  tmp <- xtrn
  colnames(tmp) <- NULL
  trainDataMatrix <- as.matrix(tmp[,-ncol(tmp)])
  #ensure outliers of training set are not used
  Ltrn <- xtrn[,ncol(xtrn)]
  trainDataMatrix <- trainDataMatrix[Ltrn==0,,drop=FALSE] #inliers
  
  #compute scores using training set: 
  #use all training objects to estimate density at training object locations 
  Ptrn <- numeric(0)
  colnames(xtrn) <- NULL

  #break into blocks to make scalable
  n <- dim(trainDataMatrix)[1]
  kmax <- max(k)
    
  Q <- array(0,dim=c(1000,dim(trainDataMatrix)[2],ceiling(n/1000)))
  flag <- 0 
  for (i in 1:ceiling(n/1000)){
    tmp <- trainDataMatrix[(1000*(i-1)+1):min(1000*i,n),,drop=FALSE]
    if(dim(tmp)[1] < 1000) {
      pad <- rbind(tmp,matrix(0,nrow=1000-dim(tmp)[1],ncol=dim(trainDataMatrix)[2]))
      Q[,,i] <- pad
      flag <- 1
      realsize <- dim(tmp)[1]
    }
    else Q[,,i] <- tmp
  }
    
  wideP <- numeric(0)
  corrected_order <- matrix(NA,nrow=1000*ceiling(n/1000),ncol=kmax*ceiling(n/1000))
  dist <- matrix(NA,nrow=1000*ceiling(n/1000),ncol=kmax*ceiling(n/1000))
  K <- matrix(0,nrow=1000*ceiling(n/1000),ncol=ceiling(n/1000))
  for (i in 1:(ceiling(n/1000))){
    if(verbose) print(paste("training: batch...",ceiling(n/1000)-i)) 
    for (j in 1:(ceiling(n/1000))){
      block <- cdist(Q[,,i],Q[,,j],metric="euclidean")
      gblock <- 1/(h*sqrt(2*pi))*exp(-0.5*(block/h)^2) 
      if (j == ceiling(n/1000) & flag == 1) {
        s <- apply(gblock[,1:realsize],1,sum)
        #for knn part
        o <- t(apply(block[,1:realsize],1,order,decreasing=FALSE))
        sorted <- t(apply(block[,1:realsize],1,sort,decreasing=FALSE))
        mn <- min(kmax,realsize)
        corrected_order[(1000*(i-1)+1):(1000*i),(1+((j-1)*kmax)):(mn+((j-1)*kmax))] <- o[,1:mn,drop=FALSE] + (1000*(j-1))
        dist[(1000*(i-1)+1):(1000*i),(1+((j-1)*kmax)):(mn+((j-1)*kmax))] <- sorted[,1:mn,drop=FALSE]
      } 
      else {
        s <- apply(gblock,1,sum) #reduce block to column
        #for knn part
        o <- t(apply(block,1,order,decreasing=FALSE))
        sorted <- t(apply(block,1,sort,decreasing=FALSE))
        corrected_order[(1000*(i-1)+1):(1000*i),(1+((j-1)*kmax)):(kmax+((j-1)*kmax))] <- o[,1:kmax,drop=FALSE] + (1000*(j-1))
        dist[(1000*(i-1)+1):(1000*i),(1+((j-1)*kmax)):(kmax+((j-1)*kmax))] <- sorted[,1:kmax,drop=FALSE]
      }
      K[(1000*(i-1)+1):(1000*i),j] <- s  #fill column with the sum
    }
  }
  A <- apply(K,1,sum)
  A <- A[1:dim(trainDataMatrix)[1]]
  A <- A/dim(trainDataMatrix)[1] #ignore the padded zeros
  Ptrn <- h*sqrt(2*pi) * A  #prob. of inlier in [0,1]
  localP <- Ptrn 
  
  thr <- list()
  for (z in seq_along(k)){
    if (dim(dist)[2]==1) {
      O <- matrix(1,nrow=nrow(dist),ncol=1)
    } 
    else {
      O <- t(apply(dist,1,order,decreasing=FALSE))[,1:k[z],drop=FALSE]
    }
    nn <- matrix(NA,nrow=dim(O)[1],ncol=k[z])
    for (i in 1:dim(O)[1]){
      nn[i,] <- corrected_order[i,O[i,],drop=FALSE]
    }
    nn <- nn[1:dim(trainDataMatrix)[1],,drop=FALSE] #trim 
    Ptst <- matrix(A[nn],nrow=dim(nn)[1],byrow = FALSE)
    Ptst <- h*sqrt(2*pi) * Ptst  #prob. of inlier in [0,1]
    wideP <- apply(Ptst,1,mean)
  
    relDist <- localP - wideP 
      
    # compute threshold equivalent to fracrej
    nf <- length(relDist)
    relDistSorted <- sort(relDist,decreasing = TRUE)
    nobj_acc <- floor((1-fracrej)*nf)
    if (nobj_acc==0) {
      thr[[z]] <- Inf
    } else if (nobj_acc==nf) {
      thr[[z]] <- -Inf 
    } else thr[[z]] <- relDistSorted[nobj_acc]
  }

  #Compute score using query points  
  Pq <- numeric(0)
  colnames(xq) <- NULL
  testDataMatrix <- as.matrix(xq[,-ncol(xq)])
  
  #break into blocks to make scalable
  ntst <- dim(testDataMatrix)[1]
  ntrn <- dim(trainDataMatrix)[1]
  
  Qtst <- array(0,dim=c(1000,dim(testDataMatrix)[2],ceiling(ntst/1000)))
  for (i in 1:ceiling(ntst/1000)){
    tmp <- testDataMatrix[(1000*(i-1)+1):min(1000*i,ntst),,drop=FALSE]
    if(dim(tmp)[1] < 1000) {
      pad <- rbind(tmp,matrix(0,nrow=1000-dim(tmp)[1],ncol=dim(testDataMatrix)[2]))
      Qtst[,,i] <- pad
    }
    else Qtst[,,i] <- tmp
  }
    
  Qtrn <- array(0,dim=c(1000,dim(trainDataMatrix)[2],ceiling(ntrn/1000)))
  flag <- 0
  for (i in 1:ceiling(ntrn/1000)){
    tmp <- trainDataMatrix[(1000*(i-1)+1):min(1000*i,ntrn),,drop=FALSE]
    if(dim(tmp)[1] < 1000) {
      pad <- rbind(tmp,matrix(0,nrow=1000-dim(tmp)[1],ncol=dim(trainDataMatrix)[2]))
      Qtrn[,,i] <- pad
      flag <- 1
      realsize <- dim(tmp)[1]
    }
    else Qtrn[,,i] <- tmp
  }
    
  wideP <- numeric(0)
  corrected_order <- matrix(NA,nrow=1000*ceiling(ntst/1000),ncol=kmax*ceiling(ntrn/1000))
  dist <- matrix(NA,nrow=1000*ceiling(ntst/1000),ncol=kmax*ceiling(ntrn/1000))
  K <- matrix(0,nrow=1000*ceiling(ntst/1000),ncol=ceiling(ntrn/1000))
  for (i in 1:(ceiling(ntst/1000))){
    if(verbose) print(paste("testing: batch...:",ceiling(ntst/1000)-i)) 
    for (j in 1:(ceiling(ntrn/1000))){
      block <- cdist(Qtst[,,i],Qtrn[,,j],metric="euclidean") 
      gblock <- 1/(h*sqrt(2*pi))*exp(-0.5*(block/h)^2) 
      if (j == ceiling(ntrn/1000) & flag == 1) {
        s <- apply(gblock[,1:realsize],1,sum)
        #for knn part
        o <- t(apply(block[,1:realsize],1,order,decreasing=FALSE))
        sorted <- t(apply(block[,1:realsize],1,sort,decreasing=FALSE))
        mn <- min(kmax,realsize)
        corrected_order[(1000*(i-1)+1):(1000*i),(1+((j-1)*kmax)):(mn+((j-1)*kmax))] <- o[,1:mn,drop=FALSE] + (1000*(j-1))
        dist[(1000*(i-1)+1):(1000*i),(1+((j-1)*kmax)):(mn+((j-1)*kmax))] <- sorted[,1:mn,drop=FALSE]
        }
      else {
        s <- apply(gblock,1,sum) #reduce block to column
        #for knn part
          o <- t(apply(block,1,order,decreasing=FALSE))
        sorted <- t(apply(block,1,sort,decreasing=FALSE))
        corrected_order[(1000*(i-1)+1):(1000*i),(1+((j-1)*kmax)):(kmax+((j-1)*kmax))] <- o[,1:kmax,drop=FALSE] + (1000*(j-1))
        dist[(1000*(i-1)+1):(1000*i),(1+((j-1)*kmax)):(kmax+((j-1)*kmax))] <- sorted[,1:kmax,drop=FALSE]
      } 
      K[(1000*(i-1)+1):(1000*i),j] <- s  #fill column with the sum
    }
  }
  B <- apply(K,1,sum)
  B <- B[1:ntst]
  B <- B/ntrn #ignore the padded zeros
  Pq <- h*sqrt(2*pi) * B  #prob. of inlier in [0,1]
  localP <- Pq
    
  l <- list()
  for (z in seq_along(k)){
    if (dim(dist)[2]==1) {
      O <- matrix(1,nrow=nrow(dist),ncol=1)
    }
    else {
      O <- t(apply(dist,1,order,decreasing=FALSE))[,1:k[z],drop=FALSE]
    }
    nn <- matrix(NA,nrow=dim(O)[1],ncol=k[z])
    for (i in 1:dim(O)[1]){
      nn[i,] <- corrected_order[i,O[i,],drop=FALSE]
    }
    nn <- nn[1:ntst,,drop=FALSE]
    Ptst <- matrix(A[nn],nrow=dim(nn)[1],byrow=FALSE) #A not B
    Ptst <- h*sqrt(2*pi) * Ptst  #prob. of inlier in [0,1]
    wideP <- apply(Ptst,1,mean)
 
    f <- localP-wideP
    
    #Label test set
    Ltst <- rep(0,nrow(xq))
    Ltst[f < thr[[z]]] <- 1 #assign as outlier
    l[[z]] <- Ltst #return list to be consistent with other classifiers
  }
  return(l)
}

Hyperparameter tuning

We set up a function for tuning the hyperparameters of the relative density one-class classifier. The criterion used is balanced accuracy.

tune_rdc <- function(a_train,a_val,fracrej,k,h,verbose=TRUE){
  #a_train: labeled training set as data frame (0=inlier, 1=outlier)
  #a_val: labeled validation set as data frame
  #fracrej: range of valuea for reject fraction in [0,1]
  #k: range of values for number of neighbors k
  #h: range of values for kernel parameter h
  
  err <- array(NA,dim=c(length(fracrej),length(h),length(k)))
  
  Yl <- a_train[a_train[,ncol(a_train)]==0,]
  for (j in seq_along(fracrej)){
    if (verbose) print(paste("counter:...",length(fracrej)-j))
    for (l in seq_along(h)){
      out <- rdocc_scalable(as.matrix(Yl), as.matrix(a_val), h=h[l], k=k, 
                            fracrej = fracrej[j], verbose=FALSE)
      for (m in seq_along(k)){
        pred <- out[[m]]

        FP <- sum(pred==1 & a_val[,ncol(a_val)]==0)
        TN <- sum(pred==0 & a_val[,ncol(a_val)]==0)
        FN <- sum(pred==0 & a_val[,ncol(a_val)]==1)
        TP <- sum(pred==1 & a_val[,ncol(a_val)]==1)
          
        error <- (FP/(FP+TN)) + (FN/(FN+TP)) #= FPR + FNR
        error = error/2
        err[j,l,m] <- error
      }
    }
  }

  ind_opt <- which(err==min(err), arr.ind = TRUE)
  if (is.array(ind_opt)){
    fracrej_opt <- fracrej[ind_opt[1,1]]
    h_opt <- h[ind_opt[1,2]]
    k_opt <- k[ind_opt[1,3]]
  }
  else {
    fracrej_opt <- fracrej[ind_opt[1]]
    h_opt <- h[ind_opt[2]]
    k_opt <- k[ind_opt[3]]
  }
  l = list(fracrej_opt=fracrej_opt,k_opt=k_opt,h_opt=h_opt)
  return(l)
}

Starting from the training set, we then create a smaller training set and a validation set for tuning the hyperparameters by grid-search over a selected range of values.

#optimize hyperparameters
a0 <- a[a$label==0,]
a1 <- a[a$label==1,]
ind0 <- sample(c(1:dim(a0)[1]),size=min(1000,dim(a0)[1]),replace=FALSE)
ind1 <- sample(c(1:dim(a1)[1]),size=min(1000,dim(a1)[1]),replace=FALSE)
a_val <- rbind(a0[ind0[1:min(500,floor(length(ind0)/2))],],
               a1[ind1[1:min(500,floor(length(ind1)/2))],])
a_train <- rbind(a0[ind0[(min(500,floor(length(ind0)/2))+1):min(1000,length(ind0))],],
                         a1[ind1[(min(500,floor(length(ind1)/2))+1):min(1000,length(ind1))],])

ROC/AUC

We write a function for computing the area under the ROC curve by summing up the areas of the trapezoids that make up the curve.

auc <- function(x,y){
  #computes area under ROC curve by summing areas of trapezoids 
  dx <- diff(x)
  base1 <- y[1:(length(y)-1)] #base 1 of trapezium
  base2 <- y[2:length(y)]
  trapezium_areas <- (base1+base2)*dx/2
  auc <- sum(trapezium_areas)
  return(auc)
}
#roc curve: vary fracrej parameter and test performance on test set
R <- c(seq(1,0.1,length.out = 5),seq(0.09,0,length.out=5)) 
error_inliers <- error_outliers <- numeric(0) 
for (i in seq_along(R)){
  l <- rdocc_scalable(as.matrix(Yl), as.matrix(b), h=h_opt, k=k_opt, 
                      fracrej = R[i],verbose=FALSE)
  L <- l[[1]]
  error_outliers[i] <- sum(L==0 & b[,ncol(b)]==1)
  error_inliers[i] <- sum(L==1 & b[,ncol(b)]==0)
}

y_rdc <- 1 - (error_inliers / sum(b[,ncol(b)]==0)) #frac targets accepted
x_rdc <- (error_outliers / sum(b[,ncol(b)]==1)) #frac outliers accepted             
auc_rdc <- auc(x_rdc,y_rdc)

Median one-class classifier (MOCC)

We implement a scalable version of the median one-class classifier (MOCC) to avoid memory overload when computing distance matrices. The implementation divides the work into manageable blocks.

mocc_scalable <- function(xtrn, xq, k = 1, fracrej = 0.05, verbose = TRUE){
  #labeled training set xtrn should contain inliers only
  #labeled query points xq (test set)
  #method computes the distance from a test object to the median of its k-nearest neighbors. 
  #k is a vector of number of neighbors to try out. 
  #fracrej is the fraction of training objects to reject.
  
  if(!require("rdist")) install.packages("rdist")
  library("rdist")
  
  tmp <- xtrn
  colnames(tmp) <- NULL
  trainDataMatrix <- as.matrix(tmp[,-ncol(tmp)])
  #ensure outliers of training set are not used
  Ltrn <- xtrn[,ncol(xtrn)]
  trainDataMatrix <- trainDataMatrix[Ltrn==0,,drop=FALSE] #inliers

  colnames(xtrn) <- NULL
  
  #break into blocks to make scalable
  n <- dim(trainDataMatrix)[1]
  kmax <- max(k)
  
  Q <- array(0,dim=c(1000,dim(trainDataMatrix)[2],ceiling(n/1000)))
  flag <- 0 
  for (i in 1:ceiling(n/1000)){
    tmp <- trainDataMatrix[(1000*(i-1)+1):min(1000*i,n),,drop=FALSE]
    if(dim(tmp)[1] < 1000) {
      pad <- rbind(tmp,matrix(0,nrow=1000-dim(tmp)[1],ncol=dim(trainDataMatrix)[2]))
      Q[,,i] <- pad
      flag <- 1
      realsize <- dim(tmp)[1]
    }
    else Q[,,i] <- tmp
  }
  
  wideP <- numeric(0)
  corrected_order <- matrix(NA,nrow=1000*ceiling(n/1000),ncol=kmax*ceiling(n/1000))
  dist <- matrix(NA,nrow=1000*ceiling(n/1000),ncol=kmax*ceiling(n/1000))
  for (i in 1:(ceiling(n/1000))){
    if(verbose) print(paste("training: batch...",ceiling(n/1000)-i)) 
    for (j in 1:(ceiling(n/1000))){
      block <- cdist(Q[,,i],Q[,,j],metric="euclidean")
      if (j == ceiling(n/1000) & flag == 1) {
        #for knn part
        o <- t(apply(block[,1:realsize],1,order,decreasing=FALSE))
        sorted <- t(apply(block[,1:realsize],1,sort,decreasing=FALSE))
        mn <- min(kmax,realsize)
        corrected_order[(1000*(i-1)+1):(1000*i),(1+((j-1)*kmax)):(mn+((j-1)*kmax))] <- o[,1:mn,drop=FALSE] + (1000*(j-1))
        dist[(1000*(i-1)+1):(1000*i),(1+((j-1)*kmax)):(mn+((j-1)*kmax))] <- sorted[,1:mn,drop=FALSE]
      } 
      else {
        #for knn part
        o <- t(apply(block,1,order,decreasing=FALSE))
        sorted <- t(apply(block,1,sort,decreasing=FALSE))
        corrected_order[(1000*(i-1)+1):(1000*i),(1+((j-1)*kmax)):(kmax+((j-1)*kmax))] <- o[,1:kmax,drop=FALSE] + (1000*(j-1))
        dist[(1000*(i-1)+1):(1000*i),(1+((j-1)*kmax)):(kmax+((j-1)*kmax))] <- sorted[,1:kmax,drop=FALSE]
      }
    }
  }

  thr <- list()
  for (z in seq_along(k)){
    if (dim(dist)[2]==1) {
      O <- matrix(1,nrow=nrow(dist),ncol=1)
    } 
    else {
      O <- t(apply(dist,1,order,decreasing=FALSE))[,1:k[z],drop=FALSE]
    }
    nn <- matrix(NA,nrow=dim(O)[1],ncol=k[z])
    for (i in 1:dim(O)[1]){
      nn[i,] <- corrected_order[i,O[i,],drop=FALSE]
    }
    nn <- nn[1:dim(trainDataMatrix)[1],,drop=FALSE] #trim 
    
    relDist <- c()
    for (i in 1:nrow(nn)){
      xmed <- apply(trainDataMatrix[nn[i,], ,drop=FALSE],2,median) #compute median feature values
      relDist[i] <- sqrt(sum((trainDataMatrix[i,] - xmed)^2))
    }
    # compute threshold equivalent to fracrej
    nf <- length(relDist)
    relDistSorted <- sort(relDist,decreasing = FALSE)
    nobj_acc <- floor((1-fracrej)*nf)
    if (nobj_acc==0) {
      thr[[z]] <- -Inf
    } else if (nobj_acc==nf) {
      thr[[z]] <- Inf 
    } else thr[[z]] <- relDistSorted[nobj_acc]
  }
  
  #Compute score using query points  
  colnames(xq) <- NULL
  testDataMatrix <- as.matrix(xq[,-ncol(xq)])
  
  #break into blocks to make scalable
  ntst <- dim(testDataMatrix)[1]
  ntrn <- dim(trainDataMatrix)[1]
  
  Qtst <- array(0,dim=c(1000,dim(testDataMatrix)[2],ceiling(ntst/1000)))
  for (i in 1:ceiling(ntst/1000)){
    tmp <- testDataMatrix[(1000*(i-1)+1):min(1000*i,ntst),,drop=FALSE]
    if(dim(tmp)[1] < 1000) {
      pad <- rbind(tmp,matrix(0,nrow=1000-dim(tmp)[1],ncol=dim(testDataMatrix)[2]))
      Qtst[,,i] <- pad
    }
    else Qtst[,,i] <- tmp
  }
  
  Qtrn <- array(0,dim=c(1000,dim(trainDataMatrix)[2],ceiling(ntrn/1000)))
  flag <- 0
  for (i in 1:ceiling(ntrn/1000)){
    tmp <- trainDataMatrix[(1000*(i-1)+1):min(1000*i,ntrn),,drop=FALSE]
    if(dim(tmp)[1] < 1000) {
      pad <- rbind(tmp,matrix(0,nrow=1000-dim(tmp)[1],ncol=dim(trainDataMatrix)[2]))
      Qtrn[,,i] <- pad
      flag <- 1
      realsize <- dim(tmp)[1]
    }
    else Qtrn[,,i] <- tmp
  }
  
  corrected_order <- matrix(NA,nrow=1000*ceiling(ntst/1000),ncol=kmax*ceiling(ntrn/1000))
  dist <- matrix(NA,nrow=1000*ceiling(ntst/1000),ncol=kmax*ceiling(ntrn/1000))
  for (i in 1:(ceiling(ntst/1000))){
    if(verbose) print(paste("testing: batch...:",ceiling(ntst/1000)-i)) 
    for (j in 1:(ceiling(ntrn/1000))){
      block <- cdist(Qtst[,,i],Qtrn[,,j],metric="euclidean") 
      if (j == ceiling(ntrn/1000) & flag == 1) {
        #for knn part
        o <- t(apply(block[,1:realsize],1,order,decreasing=FALSE))
        sorted <- t(apply(block[,1:realsize],1,sort,decreasing=FALSE))
        mn <- min(kmax,realsize)
        corrected_order[(1000*(i-1)+1):(1000*i),(1+((j-1)*kmax)):(mn+((j-1)*kmax))] <- o[,1:mn,drop=FALSE] + (1000*(j-1))
        dist[(1000*(i-1)+1):(1000*i),(1+((j-1)*kmax)):(mn+((j-1)*kmax))] <- sorted[,1:mn,drop=FALSE]
      }
      else {
        #for knn part
        o <- t(apply(block,1,order,decreasing=FALSE))
        sorted <- t(apply(block,1,sort,decreasing=FALSE))
        corrected_order[(1000*(i-1)+1):(1000*i),(1+((j-1)*kmax)):(kmax+((j-1)*kmax))] <- o[,1:kmax,drop=FALSE] + (1000*(j-1))
        dist[(1000*(i-1)+1):(1000*i),(1+((j-1)*kmax)):(kmax+((j-1)*kmax))] <- sorted[,1:kmax,drop=FALSE]
      } 
    }
  }

  l <- list()
  for (z in seq_along(k)){
    if (dim(dist)[2]==1) {
      O <- matrix(1,nrow=nrow(dist),ncol=1)
    }
    else {
      O <- t(apply(dist,1,order,decreasing=FALSE))[,1:k[z],drop=FALSE]
    }
    nn <- matrix(NA,nrow=dim(O)[1],ncol=k[z])
    for (i in 1:dim(O)[1]){
      nn[i,] <- corrected_order[i,O[i,],drop=FALSE]
    }
    nn <- nn[1:ntst,,drop=FALSE]
  
    f <- c()
    for (i in 1:nrow(nn)){
      xmed <- apply(trainDataMatrix[nn[i,], ,drop=FALSE],2,median) #compute median feature values
      f[i] <- sqrt(sum((testDataMatrix[i,] - xmed)^2))
    }
    
    #Label test set
    Ltst <- rep(0,nrow(xq))
    Ltst[f > thr[[z]]] <- 1 #assign as outlier
    l[[z]] <- Ltst #return list to be consistent with other classifiers
  }
  return(l)
}

Hyperparameter tuning

We set up a function for tuning the hyperparameters of MOCC. The criterion used is balanced accuracy.

tune_mocc <- function(a_train,a_val,fracrej,k,verbose=TRUE){
  #a_train: labeled training set as data frame (0=inlier, 1=outlier)
  #a_val: labeled validation set as data frame
  #fracrej: range of valuea for reject fraction in [0,1]
  #k: range of values for number of neighbors k

  err <- array(NA,dim=c(length(fracrej),length(k)))
  
  Yl <- a_train[a_train[,ncol(a_train)]==0,]
  for (j in seq_along(fracrej)){
    if (verbose) print(paste("counter:...",length(fracrej)-j))
    #for (l in seq_along(h)){
      out <- mocc_scalable(as.matrix(Yl), as.matrix(a_val), k=k, 
                            fracrej = fracrej[j], verbose=FALSE)
      for (m in seq_along(k)){
        pred <- out[[m]]
        
        FP <- sum(pred==1 & a_val[,ncol(a_val)]==0)
        TN <- sum(pred==0 & a_val[,ncol(a_val)]==0)
        FN <- sum(pred==0 & a_val[,ncol(a_val)]==1)
        TP <- sum(pred==1 & a_val[,ncol(a_val)]==1)
        
        error <- (FP/(FP+TN)) + (FN/(FN+TP)) #= FPR + FNR
        error = error/2
        err[j,m] <- error
    #  }
    }
  }
  
  ind_opt <- which(err==min(err), arr.ind = TRUE)
  if (is.array(ind_opt)){
    fracrej_opt <- fracrej[ind_opt[1,1]]
    k_opt <- k[ind_opt[1,2]]
  }
  else {
    fracrej_opt <- fracrej[ind_opt[1]]
    k_opt <- k[ind_opt[2]]
  }
  l = list(fracrej_opt=fracrej_opt,k_opt=k_opt)
  return(l)
}

Isolation forest

We write a wrapper function around the isolation forest classifier allowing for a reject fraction.

iForest <- function(xtrn, xtst, fracrej, sample_size = 256){
  #isolation forest: 
  #xtrn: labeled training set, should contain inliers only
  #xtst: labeled test set can contain inliers and outliers
  #fracrej is the fraction of training objects to reject as outliers.
  #sample_size: number of objects used to build a tree in the forest
  
  if(!require("solitude")) install.packages("solitude")
  library("solitude")
  
  isf <- isolationForest$new(sample_size = sample_size)  # initiate
  x <- as.data.frame(xtrn[,-ncol(xtrn)])
  isf$fit(x)
  #isf$scores #anomaly scores 
  #scores closer to 1 => outliers
  s <- isf$predict(x) # scores for training set
  ss <- sort(s$anomaly_score, decreasing = TRUE)
  nrej <- ceiling(fracrej * length(ss))
  if (fracrej==1) thr <- -Inf
  else if (fracrej==0) thr <- Inf
  else thr <- ss[nrej]

  y <- as.data.frame(xtst[,-ncol(xtst)])
  s <- isf$predict(y) # scores for test set
  out <- (s$anomaly_score > thr)
  out <- as.numeric(out)
  return(list(out))
}

Hyperparameter tuning

We tune an isolation forest classifier using a wrapper function through which we identify the optimal reject fraction based on the criterion of balanced accuracy.

tune_iforest <- function(a_train,a_val,fracrej,verbose=TRUE){
  #a_train: labeled training set as data frame (0=inlier, 1=outlier)
  #a_val: labeled validation set as data frame
  #fracrej: range of values for reject fraction in [0,1]
  
  err <- rep(NA,length(fracrej))
  Yl <- a_train[a_train[,ncol(a_train)]==0,]
  x <- as.data.frame(Yl)
  y <- as.data.frame(a_val)
  colnames(y) <- colnames(x)
  for (j in seq_along(fracrej)){
    if (verbose) print(paste("counter:...",length(fracrej)-j))
    out <- iForest(x,y,fracrej=fracrej[j],sample_size = dim(x)[1])
    pred <- out[[1]]

    FP <- sum(pred==1 & a_val[,ncol(a_val)]==0)
    TN <- sum(pred==0 & a_val[,ncol(a_val)]==0)
    FN <- sum(pred==0 & a_val[,ncol(a_val)]==1)
    TP <- sum(pred==1 & a_val[,ncol(a_val)]==1)
      
    error <- (FP/(FP+TN)) + (FN/(FN+TP)) #= FPR + FNR
    error = error/2
    err[j] <- error
  }

  ind_opt <- which(err==min(err))#, arr.ind = TRUE)
  fracrej_opt <- fracrej[ind_opt[1]]

  l = list(fracrej_opt=fracrej_opt)
  return(l)
}

Support vector machine

Hyperparameter tuning

We tune a support vector machine based on the criterion of balanced accuracy.

tune_svm <- function(a_train,a_val,nu,gamma,verbose=TRUE){
  #a_train: labeled training set as data frame (0=inlier, 1=outlier)
  #a_val: labeled validation set as data frame
  #nu: range of values in ]0,1[
  #gamma: range of values for gamma
  
  err <- matrix(NA,nrow=length(nu),ncol=length(gamma))
  Yl <- a_train[a_train[,ncol(a_train)]==0,]
  x <- as.data.frame(Yl)
  y <- as.data.frame(a_val)
  colnames(y) <- colnames(x)
  for (j in seq_along(nu)){
    if(verbose) print(paste("counter:...",length(nu)-j))
    for (l in seq_along(gamma)){
      model <- svm(x = x[,-ncol(x)], y = x[,ncol(x)], type="one-classification",
                   kernel="radial",nu=nu[j],gamma = gamma[l])
      pred <- predict(model, y[,-ncol(y)])
      pred <- as.numeric(!pred)
      #err[i,j,l] <- sum(pred!=y[,ncol(y)])
        
      FP <- sum(pred==1 & a_val[,ncol(a_val)]==0)
      TN <- sum(pred==0 & a_val[,ncol(a_val)]==0)
      FN <- sum(pred==0 & a_val[,ncol(a_val)]==1)
      TP <- sum(pred==1 & a_val[,ncol(a_val)]==1)
        
      error <- (FP/(FP+TN)) + (FN/(FN+TP)) #= FPR + FNR
      error = error/2
      err[j,l] <- error
      }
    }
  
  ind_opt <- which(err==min(err), arr.ind = TRUE)
  if (is.array(ind_opt)){
    nu_opt <- nu[ind_opt[1,1]]
    gamma_opt <- gamma[ind_opt[1,2]]
  }
  else {
    nu_opt <- nu[ind_opt[1]]
    gamma_opt <- gamma[ind_opt[2]]
  }
  
  l = list(nu_opt=nu_opt,gamma_opt=gamma_opt)
  return(l)
}
#optimize hyperparameters
nu <- seq(0.01,0.99,length.out = 40)
gamma <- seq(0.01,0.99,length.out = 40)

l <- tune_svm(a_train,a_val,nu,gamma,verbose=FALSE)
nu_opt <- l$nu_opt
gamma_opt <- l$gamma_opt

Local outlier factor

We write a wrapper function around the local outlier factor classifier allowing for a reject fraction. Normally this classifier is for an unsupervised setting, so we compute the anomaly score of one test object at a time (given the training set and the particular test object). In other words, we have extended the classifier to return labels for new test objects.

lof_wrapper <- function(xtrn, xtst, k = 5, fracrej = 0.01, cores=2){
  #local outlier factor: 
  #xtrn: labeled training set, should contain inliers only
  #xtst: labeled test set can contain both inliers and outliers 
  #k: number of neighbors to consider
  #fracrej: the fraction of training objects to reject as outliers.
  #cores: number of CPUs to run in parallel
  
  if(!require("Rlof")) install.packages("Rlof")
  library("Rlof")
  
  x <- xtrn[,-ncol(xtrn)]
  scores_training <- lof(x,k,cores)
  if (length(k)==1) scores_training <- as.matrix(scores_training)
  
  out <- list()
  for (z in seq_along(k)){
    ss <- sort(scores_training[,z], decreasing = TRUE)
    nrej <- ceiling(fracrej * length(ss))
    if (fracrej==1) thr <- -Inf
    else if (fracrej==0) thr <- Inf
    else thr <- ss[nrej]
    
    tmp <- rep(0,dim(xtst)[1])
    for (i in 1:dim(xtst)[1]){
      score <- lof(rbind(x,xtst[i,-ncol(xtst)]),k,cores)
      if(length(k)==1) score <- as.matrix(score)
      tmp[i] <- as.numeric(score[nrow(score),z] > thr)
    }
    out[[z]] <- tmp
  }
  return(out)
}

Hyperparameter tuning

We tune a local outlier factor (LOF) classifier based on the criterion of balanced accuracy.

tune_lof <- function(a_train,a_val,fracrej,k,verbose=TRUE){
  #a_train: labeled training set as data frame (0=inlier, 1=outlier)
  #a_val: labeled validation set as data frame
  #fracrej: range of values for reject fraction in [0,1]
  #k: range of values for number of neighbors 
  
  err <- matrix(NA,nrow=length(fracrej),ncol=length(k))
  Yl <- a_train[a_train[,ncol(a_train)]==0,]
  x <- as.data.frame(Yl)
  y <- as.data.frame(a_val)
  colnames(y) <- colnames(x)
  for (j in seq_along(fracrej)){
    if(verbose) print(paste("counter:...",length(fracrej)-j))
      out <- lof_wrapper(x, y, k = k, fracrej = fracrej[j], cores=1)
      for (l in seq_along(k)){
        pred <- out[[l]]

        FP <- sum(pred==1 & a_val[,ncol(a_val)]==0)
        TN <- sum(pred==0 & a_val[,ncol(a_val)]==0)
        FN <- sum(pred==0 & a_val[,ncol(a_val)]==1)
        TP <- sum(pred==1 & a_val[,ncol(a_val)]==1)
      
        error <- (FP/(FP+TN)) + (FN/(FN+TP)) #= FPR + FNR
        error = error/2
        err[j,l] <- error
    }
  }
  
  ind_opt <- which(err==min(err), arr.ind = TRUE)
  if (is.array(ind_opt)){
    fracrej_opt <- fracrej[ind_opt[1,1]]
    k_opt <- k[ind_opt[1,2]]
  }
  else {
    fracrej_opt <- fracrej[ind_opt[1]]
    k_opt <- k[ind_opt[2]]
  }
  
  l = list(fracrej_opt=fracrej_opt,k_opt=k_opt)
  return(l)
}

We use a small training set and validation set when tuning due to the high computational expense of this classifier. We also assume a nearest neighbor hyperparameter of 20 neighbors at most.

Multi-class classification

Classify network patterns as normal (=0), Probe (=1), Dos (=2), U2R (=3), or R2L( =4). The training set contains 23 different types (between normal and attack) which are categorized into one of the 5 classes above, whereas the test set contains 38 different types (between normal and attack) which are also categorized into the above 5 classes. There are 17 attack types appearing only in the test set: apache2 (DoS), httptunnel (R2L), mailbomb (DoS), mscan (Probe), named (R2L), processtable (DoS), ps (U2R), saint (Probe), sendmail (R2L), snmpgetattack (R2L), snmpguess (R2L), sqlattack (U2R), udpstorm (DoS), worm (DoS), xlock (R2L), xsnoop (R2L), and xterm (U2R). In this work, we do not treat these attack types appearing only in the test set as an “unknown” class, but rather we consider these as relating to novel probing, DoS, U2R, or R2L attacks.

Multiple one-class classifiers

We train a one-class relative density one-class classifier in a one-against-all scheme for each of the 5 classes: normal, Probe, DoS, U2R, or R2L, followed by a majority vote. Ties are broken by assigning to the class with the nearest mean from among the classes that are in tie. In case an object is rejected as outlier by all 5 classifiers, it is assigned to the class with the nearest mean.

Normalization

We first drop any irrelavant (non-varying) features and normalize the data based on the training set.

#drop irrelevant features 
n <- dim(xtrn)[1]
a <- xtrn[,-ncol(xtrn)]
sdev <- apply(a,2,sd)
idx <- which(sdev==0) #irrelevant features to learn on
print(idx)
## num_outbound_cmds 
##               101
xtrn <- xtrn[,-idx] #drop irrelevant features
xtst <- xtst[,-idx]

#normalize
a <- xtrn[,-ncol(xtrn)]
mu <- apply(a,2,mean)
sdev <- apply(a,2,sd)
a <- (a-matrix(1,n,1)%*%mu)/(matrix(1,n,1)%*%sdev)
a$label <- xtrn[,ncol(xtrn)]

#normalize test set using only info from training set
ntst <- dim(xtst)[1]
b <- xtst[,-ncol(xtst)]
b <- (b-matrix(1,ntst,1)%*%mu)/(matrix(1,ntst,1)%*%sdev)
b$label <- xtst[,ncol(xtst)]

Train a local outlier factor classifier on R2L-vs.-all case. The value of hyperparameterss are estimated in the same manner as described previously. Finally, the ROC curve and the AUC value are computed and stored.

#optimize hyperparameters
a_val <- rbind(a0[ind0[1:min(50,floor(length(ind0)/2))],],
               a1[ind1[1:min(50,floor(length(ind1)/2))],])
a_train <- rbind(a0[ind0[(min(50,floor(length(ind0)/2))+1):min(100,length(ind0))],],
                         a1[ind1[(min(50,floor(length(ind1)/2))+1):min(100,length(ind1))],])

fracrej <- seq(0.01,0.3,length.out = 10)
k <- seq(2,min(20,sum(a_train$label==0)-1),by=3) 

l <- tune_lof(a_train,a_val,fracrej,k,verbose=FALSE)
fracrej_opt <- l$fracrej_opt
k_opt <- l$k_opt

b0 <- zb[zb$label==0,]
b1 <- zb[zb$label==1,]
ind0 <- sample(c(1:dim(b0)[1]),size=min(100,dim(b0)[1]),replace=FALSE)
ind1 <- sample(c(1:dim(b1)[1]),size=min(100,dim(b1)[1]),replace=FALSE)
b_test <- rbind(b0[ind0,],b1[ind1,])

Yl <- a_train[a_train$label==0,]
x <- as.data.frame(Yl)
y <- as.data.frame(b_test)
colnames(y) <- colnames(x)

out <- lof_wrapper(x, y, k = k_opt, fracrej = fracrej_opt, cores=1)
pred <- out[[1]]
cf <- confusionMatrix(factor(pred,levels=c(0,1)),
                      factor(y[,ncol(y)],levels=c(0,1)), positive="1")
cntR2L_lof <- as.numeric(pred==0) #counter for R2L attack

Majority vote

A majority vote among the 5 classifiers decides the label of a given test object. Ties are broken by assigning to the class with the nearest mean from among the classes that are in tie. In case an object is rejected as outlier by all 5 classifiers, it is assigned to the class with the nearest mean.

Relative density one-class classifier (RDOCC)

#majority vote: rdc
votes <- cbind(cntN_rdc, cntProbe_rdc, cntDoS_rdc, cntU2R_rdc, cntR2L_rdc) #binary
predicted_labels <- rep(NA,dim(xtst)[1])
s <- apply(votes,1,sum)
idx <- which(s==1)
predicted_labels[idx] <- (max.col(votes[idx,])-1)

M <- rbind(mean_normal, mean_probe, mean_dos, mean_u2r, mean_r2l)
idx0 <- which(s==0)
d <- cdist(b[idx0,-ncol(b)], M, metric="euclidean")
predicted_labels[idx0] <- (apply(d,1,which.min)-1)

idx_tie <- which(s>1)
for (i in seq_along(idx_tie)){
  q <- which(votes[idx_tie[i],]==1)
  t <- M[q,] 
  d <- cdist(b[idx_tie[i],-ncol(b),drop=FALSE], t, metric="euclidean")
  v <- apply(d,1,which.min)
  predicted_labels[idx_tie[i]] <- (q[v]-1)
}

#showing voting stats
df_rdc <- data.frame(unique_label = length(idx), no_label = length(idx0), tie = length(idx_tie))
print(df_rdc)
##   unique_label no_label   tie
## 1         7147     1497 13900
